  "prompt": "What is the formula to calculate a synchronous speed of a motor?",
  "response": "The formula to calculate the synchronous speed of a motor is:\n\n**Ns = (120 * f) / p**\n\nWhere:\n\n*   **Ns** = Synchronous speed in revolutions per minute (RPM)\n*   **f** = Frequency of the power supply in Hertz (Hz)\n*   **p** = Number of poles in the motor's stator winding\n\n**Explanation:**\n\n*   **120** is a constant that results from converting seconds to minutes and accommodating the relationship between poles and cycles.\n*   The **frequency (f)** represents the number of cycles of alternating current (AC) that occur per second.\n*   The **number of poles (p)** refers to the number of magnetic poles created by the stator windings.  Motors always have an even number of poles (2, 4, 6, 8, etc.).\n\n**Example:**\n\nLet's say you have a motor connected to a 60 Hz power supply and it has 4 poles. The synchronous speed would be:\n\nNs = (120 * 60) / 4 = 7200 / 4 = 1800 RPM\n\nTherefore, the synchronous speed of the motor is 1800 RPM.\n",
